          'A logical address (also called a virtual address) is the address generated by the CPU while a program runs. The program "thinks" it owns a contiguous address space starting at 0, but that is an illusion. The physical address is the actual location in main memory (RAM) where the data lives. The full set of logical addresses a program can generate is its logical address space; the corresponding real addresses form its physical address space.\n\nThe translation from logical to physical address is done by a hardware unit called the Memory Management Unit (MMU). In the simplest scheme the MMU holds a relocation (base) register. When the CPU emits logical address L, the MMU computes physical address = base + L. A limit register is also checked so that L stays within the program\'s allotted range; otherwise a trap is raised, which is the hardware basis of memory protection between processes.\n\nAddress binding can happen at three times. Compile time: if you know in advance where the process will sit in memory, absolute addresses can be generated; moving it later requires recompilation. Load time: the compiler produces relocatable code and final binding happens when the program is loaded. Execution (run) time: binding is delayed until the instruction actually executes, which is what allows a process to be moved during its lifetime — this is the common case and requires MMU hardware support.\n\nThe key benefit of run-time binding is that the operating system gains freedom to relocate, swap out, and protect processes without the program being aware. The logical address space and physical address space therefore decouple, which is the foundation that paging and virtual memory later build on.',
