        explanation:
          'In contiguous memory allocation each process is placed in a single continuous block of physical memory. Memory is divided either into fixed-size partitions or variable-size partitions (dynamic partitioning). With fixed partitions the number and size of partitions is set in advance, which is simple but wasteful. With variable partitions the OS keeps a list of free regions (holes) and carves out exactly what a process needs.\n\nWhen a process arrives, the OS must pick which free hole to use. First Fit scans from the start and uses the first hole large enough — it is fast and tends to perform well. Best Fit chooses the smallest hole that is still big enough, aiming to waste the least space, but it tends to leave many tiny unusable holes and requires scanning the whole list. Worst Fit chooses the largest hole, hoping the leftover remainder is big enough to be useful later; in practice it performs poorly.\n\nStudies generally show First Fit and Best Fit outperform Worst Fit in both speed and storage utilization, and First Fit is usually fastest. None of them eliminates fragmentation, which is the core weakness of contiguous allocation.\n\nExample: holes of sizes 100, 500, 200, 300, 600 KB and a request of 212 KB. First Fit uses the 500 KB hole (first one ≥ 212). Best Fit uses the 300 KB hole (smallest that fits). Worst Fit uses the 600 KB hole (largest). The leftover differs in each case, which is why the choice affects future allocations.',
