        explanation:
          'Virtual memory is a technique that lets a process execute even though it is not entirely in physical memory. The logical (virtual) address space can be much larger than the physical memory; the OS keeps only the actively used parts in RAM and the rest on disk (the swap area or backing store). Programs are written as if they have a large contiguous address space, and the MMU plus OS handle the illusion.\n\nThe motivation is that programs rarely need all of their code and data at once — error-handling routines, unusual options, and large arrays are often only partially touched. By loading pages on demand, the system can run programs larger than RAM, run more processes simultaneously (higher degree of multiprogramming), and start programs faster because not everything must be loaded before execution begins.\n\nVirtual memory is most commonly implemented with demand paging, where pages are brought into memory only when referenced. It can also be done with demand segmentation. The valid/invalid bit in each page-table entry marks whether a page is currently resident; referencing a non-resident page triggers a page fault that the OS services by fetching the page from disk.\n\nThe benefits are substantial: less I/O at load, less memory per process, more concurrency, and the ability to share pages (e.g. shared libraries, copy-on-write fork). The trade-off is the overhead of page faults and the risk of thrashing if too little memory is available per process.',
