        explanation:
          'Demand paging loads a page into memory only when it is referenced ("on demand"), never speculatively at start. Each page-table entry has a valid/invalid bit: valid means the page is in memory, invalid means it is either illegal or simply not yet loaded. When the CPU references a page marked invalid (but legitimate), the MMU traps to the OS — this is a page fault.\n\nThe page-fault service steps are: (1) trap to the OS and save state; (2) verify the reference is legal and find the page on the backing store; (3) find a free frame (or evict a victim using a page-replacement algorithm, writing it back if dirty); (4) schedule a disk read to load the page into the frame; (5) when I/O completes, update the page table to mark the page valid and pointing to that frame, and set bits accordingly; (6) restart the instruction that faulted, which now succeeds.\n\nEffective Access Time (EAT) captures the average cost: EAT = (1 − p) × memory_access_time + p × page_fault_service_time, where p is the page-fault rate (0 ≤ p ≤ 1). Page-fault service time is dominated by disk I/O and is many orders of magnitude slower than memory.\n\nNumeric example: memory access = 200 ns, page-fault service = 8 ms = 8,000,000 ns. With p = 0.001 (1 fault per 1000 accesses): EAT = (1 − 0.001) × 200 + 0.001 × 8,000,000 = 199.8 + 8000 = 8199.8 ns, about 40× slower than raw memory. This shows page faults must be rare (p well below 0.001) to keep performance acceptable, which is why locality and good replacement matter so much.',
