        explanation:
          'Copy-on-write is an optimization used most prominently when a process forks. Instead of immediately duplicating the entire parent address space for the child, the OS lets parent and child share the same physical frames, marking those shared pages read-only (and recording that they are copy-on-write). As long as both processes only read, no copying happens and memory and time are saved.\n\nWhen either process attempts to write to a shared COW page, the hardware raises a protection fault. The OS catches it, allocates a new frame, copies the page contents into it, updates the writing process\'s page table to point at the private copy with write permission, and resumes. Only pages that are actually modified get copied; untouched pages stay shared.\n\nThis is hugely beneficial for the common fork-then-exec pattern: a shell forks and the child immediately calls exec to load a new program, so copying the parent\'s entire memory would be wasted work. With COW the fork is cheap and most pages are never copied. It also benefits memory-mapped files and shared libraries.\n\nThe key insight for interviews: COW defers (and often avoids) the expensive copy until a write proves it necessary, trading a cheap page-fault on first write for potentially huge savings in memory and copy time. The dirty/modified accounting and read-only protection bit are what make it work.',
