        summary: 'Evicting the oldest page, the unimplementable best, and the surprising FIFO anomaly.',
        explanation:
          'FIFO (First-In-First-Out) evicts the page that has been in memory the longest, regardless of how often it is used. It is trivial to implement with a queue but performs poorly because a heavily used old page can be evicted just for being old.\n\nThe Optimal algorithm (OPT / MIN, Belady\'s algorithm) evicts the page that will not be used for the longest time in the future. It produces the minimum possible number of page faults and is used as a benchmark, but it is impossible to implement in practice because it requires knowledge of future references.\n\nWorked example with the reference string 7 0 1 2 0 3 0 4 2 3 and 3 frames. FIFO: faults at 7,0,1 (fill), 2 evicts 7, 0 hit, 3 evicts 0, 0 evicts 1, 4 evicts 2, 2 evicts 3, 3 evicts 0 — counting carefully FIFO yields about 7-8 faults depending on the exact string; Optimal on the same string yields fewer because it evicts pages not needed soon. The general lesson is OPT ≤ LRU ≤ FIFO in fault count for typical strings.\n\nBelady\'s anomaly is the counter-intuitive phenomenon where increasing the number of frames can increase the number of page faults under FIFO. The classic example is reference string 1 2 3 4 1 2 5 1 2 3 4 5: with 3 frames FIFO produces 9 faults, but with 4 frames it produces 10 faults — more memory, more faults. FIFO suffers this because it is not a stack algorithm (the set of pages in N frames is not guaranteed to be a subset of the set in N+1 frames). LRU and Optimal are stack algorithms and never exhibit Belady\'s anomaly.',
