        topic: 'LRU & Its Approximations (Clock / Second-Chance)',
        summary: 'Evicting the least-recently-used page and the cheap clock approximation real systems use.',
        explanation:
          'LRU (Least Recently Used) evicts the page that has not been used for the longest time, using the past as a predictor of the future. By the principle of locality, a page not referenced recently is unlikely to be referenced soon, so LRU closely approximates Optimal and is a stack algorithm (no Belady\'s anomaly).\n\nExact LRU is expensive to implement. Two hardware approaches exist: a counter scheme stamps each page-table entry with a logical clock value on every reference and the victim is the entry with the smallest stamp (requires writing memory on every access and a search at eviction); a stack scheme keeps a doubly linked list of page numbers moved to the top on each reference, so the bottom is the LRU victim. Both require hardware support on every memory reference, which is costly — this is why exact LRU is rarely implemented directly.\n\nThe clock (second-chance) algorithm is the common practical approximation. It uses only a single reference bit per page set by hardware on access. Pages are arranged in a circular list with a pointer (clock hand). To find a victim, the hand advances; if a page\'s reference bit is 0, it is evicted; if 1, the bit is cleared to 0 (giving the page a second chance) and the hand moves on. A frequently used page keeps getting its bit set and survives, while a stale page is eventually evicted. An enhanced version also uses the dirty bit to prefer evicting clean pages.\n\nFor interviews, the headline is: LRU is near-optimal but hard to do exactly because it needs per-reference bookkeeping; clock/second-chance approximates it cheaply with one reference bit, which is what real operating systems use.',
