        summary: 'Using locality to size each process\'s frame allotment and keep page-fault rate in range.',
        explanation:
          'The principle of locality of reference states that over short periods a process accesses a relatively small, slowly-changing set of pages. Temporal locality means a recently used page is likely to be used again soon; spatial locality means addresses near a referenced one are likely to be used. Locality is why caching, the TLB, and demand paging all work.\n\nThe working-set model formalizes locality. The working set W(t, Δ) is the set of pages referenced in the most recent Δ references (the working-set window). Its size, the working-set size (WSS), estimates how many frames the process currently needs. If the OS ensures the sum of all processes\' working-set sizes does not exceed the total frames, thrashing is avoided; if it would exceed, the OS suspends (swaps out) a process. Choosing Δ matters: too small misses the locality, too large spans several localities.\n\nThe page-fault-frequency (PFF) scheme controls allocation more directly by monitoring each process\'s actual page-fault rate. An upper and lower bound are set: if a process\'s fault rate exceeds the upper bound, it needs more frames, so the OS gives it another; if it drops below the lower bound, the process has too many frames, so one is taken away. PFF reacts to observed behavior rather than estimating the working set.\n\nFor frame allocation across processes, two basic policies exist: equal allocation gives every process the same number of frames; proportional allocation gives frames in proportion to process size (or priority), which is fairer since larger processes need more frames. These are combined with local vs global replacement to manage the overall system.',
