        links: [
          { label: 'GeeksforGeeks', url: 'https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/file-allocation-methods/' },
        ],
        interview: [
          { q: 'Compare contiguous, linked, and indexed file allocation.', a: 'Contiguous stores a file in consecutive blocks — fast sequential and direct access but external fragmentation and growth problems. Linked scatters blocks with next-pointers — easy growth and no external fragmentation but slow random access. Indexed uses a per-file index block of pointers — good random access with some space overhead.' },
          { q: 'What is the main drawback of contiguous allocation?', a: 'External fragmentation and the difficulty of growing a file: free space fragments into holes, and you must know the file size in advance because extending a file may be impossible if adjacent blocks are occupied.' },
          { q: 'Why is direct (random) access slow with linked allocation?', a: 'Blocks are scattered and chained by pointers, so reaching block i requires following i pointers from the file\'s first block. There is no formula to compute a block\'s location, unlike contiguous or indexed allocation.' },
          { q: 'How do Unix inodes handle very large files?', a: 'An inode has several direct block pointers plus single, double, and triple indirect pointers. Indirect pointers reference blocks of pointers, multiplying capacity so small files use only direct pointers while huge files scale via the indirect levels.' },
          { q: 'What is the FAT (File Allocation Table) method?', a: 'FAT is a variant of linked allocation that stores all the next-block pointers in a single table at the start of the volume, indexed by block number. Keeping the table in memory speeds up random access compared to chasing pointers stored inside each data block.' },
        ],
